Next, let us try k=1. When k=1, we get that 
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{18}+\frac{2\pi}{3}=\frac{13\pi}{18} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta = \frac{5\pi}{18}+\frac{2\pi}{3}=\frac{17\pi}{18} 
Since both of these values are between -\pi and \pi, we include them in our solution set.

If we try the next value of k=2, we get that
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{18}+\frac{4\pi}{3}=\frac{25\pi}{18} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta = \frac{5\pi}{18}+\frac{4\pi}{3}=\frac{29\pi}{18} 
Since both of these values are greater than \pi, we do not include them in our solution set. Moreover, we do not need to test any values of k greater than 2 since those values will also give us angles of \theta greater than /pi.

If k=-1, we get that
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{18}-\frac{2\pi}{3}=-\frac{11\pi}{18} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta = \frac{5\pi}{18}-\frac{2\pi}{3}=-\frac{7\pi}{18}  
Since both of these values are between -\pi and \pi, we include them in our solution set.

Next, let us try k=-2. When k=-2, we get that
 \theta = \frac{\pi}{18}-\frac{4\pi}{3}=-\frac{23\pi}{18} \hspace{.25in} \text{and} \hspace{.25in} \theta = \frac{5\pi}{18}-\frac{4\pi}{3}=-\frac{19\pi}{18} 
Since both of these values are less than -\pi, we do not include them in our solution set. Moreover, we do not need to test any values of k less than -2 since those values will also give us angles of \theta less than -\pi. Thus, we have found all solutions to 2\sin(3\theta)=1 in the interval [-\pi,\pi].
